<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> &quot;Sad to me that in todays society sooo many people base their ideas and beliefs on scientific based thought. Scientific based thought doesn't encounter such a thing as 'afterlife' and because science is empirical it will never encounter life after death. Science in this case is limited.&quot;<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I agree that the scientific community would be hard pressed to offer a viable explanation of &quot;life after death&quot;. However, that is because science in general is about what can be observed in principle and doesn't like to muck about with things that should be left to theologians and philosophers to ponder, such as &quot;Life after death&quot;. We should not be quick to condemn Empiricism out right. I am not an Empircist (as you indicate), but rather a Pragmatist. As such, I do not even think of trying to convince others that there is no life after death. Hey, if belief in an afterlife comforts people then why even try to take it away? It works in providing many benefits to people. Hell, if people will obey the laws because they think they will burn in hell I benefit! Let them believe, but because I fail to believe doesn't mean that I am magically bereft of feeling or emotion, or that I am immoral. Just because I fail to believe doesn't make me an automaton of science!<br>
